Outreach and Engagement Process  
Community outreach and engagement as part of the Thrive Inland SoCal collaborative was separated into three phases to ensure community members and key affinity groups were engaged throughout each step of developing the regional strategies and the regional economic development plan. Phase 1, Defining a Quality Job, was conducted through the outreach committees and SRTs from October 2023 through February 2024\. Phase 2, Identifying Barriers to Quality Jobs and Solutions, was conducted through SRT meetings and constituency-based focus groups (labor, reentry populations) during March and April 2024\. The final phase, Reviewing Regional Strategies, was conducted through SRT-based review committees in May 2024, with an additional round of review by these committees and the Inclusive Planning Council in July and August 2024\. The Thrive Inland SoCal conveners contracted with the Centre for Sustainable Energy (CSE) to provide outreach support to the SRTs throughout this process, and CSE took the lead on building the Thrive Engagement Map \[need link from Stephanie\], a community resource identifying participants in the Thrive Inland SoCal collaborative, and developing and analyzing the Community Insights survey during Phases 1 and 2\.

Community Insights Survey Process and Findings  
The Thrive Inland SoCal Community Insights survey was created to gather community responses to key questions, primarily on job availability, job training, and workforce advancement/preparedness in the region. Its purpose was to ensure that members of the community who may have been unable to join the meetings were still able to provide input and participate in the inclusive economic development process. 

The survey was open and available from February 13 to April 15, 2024 and distributed through Thrive Inland SoCal SRTs and committees at meetings, events, and via email. The survey was also made available in Spanish, and respondents typically took the survey on a mobile phone or computer.

A total of 711 responses were collected based on an opportunistic sample; it was not administered in a way to ensure representativeness by subregion, age, affiliation, or any other group. 289 surveys were excluded from this analysis as they were found to be duplicate, laconic, or fraudulent. The remaining 422 surveys were spread across the six sub-regional tables and two committees with the majority of responses concentrated in the four metropolitan SRTs of San Bernardino and Riverside counties. The rural SRTs of High Desert and Coachella Valley & Morongo Basin had the lowest survey participation rates, making up only 18 and 12 of the 422 responses, respectively.  

The survey identified a series of barriers to workforce advancement that resonated with respondents, including the need to build social and cultural capital, lack of career pathways, access to childcare as well as to education and training opportunities, lack of affordable housing, the need for entrepreneurship resources, and access to both reliable technology and affordable transportation options. There was notable variation in responses among the subregions (for example, Coachella/Morongo brought up transportation access as a barrier the most, while High Desert respondents highlighted access to training and education as their most significant barrier).
